<font color="#FF0000">JUDGE NO ONE</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jul  9 21:43:41 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Blessed Is the Tie That Binds<br><br>
A short while ago I received an email from a woman who is an editor of a small circulation outdoor magazine here in the southeast. Her magazine had published one of my hiking articles. She had stumbled upon my website and remarked how she thought it was &quot;neat&quot;.<br><br>
We exchanged several emails. Each time she revealed a little more of what she had read on my site, along with her feelings about the Vietnam War. The clincher came when she broke down and admitted about the time, at age 16, when she had ran away from home. She took up with some war protestors who stood outside a US military installation and shouted at departing troops, &quot;Don't go&quot;.<br><br>
When the woman, in her final post of that day told me how much she appreciated the sacrifice of those who served in Vietnam, for some reason I suspected that she may have even shouted something that was more dreadful at those troops. Perhaps. What difference does it make to a soul such as mine, that thinks - not for an instant - that it has the power to ease the pain of the folly of someone else's youth? As they said many years ago in Vietnam, &quot;Don't mean nuthin.&quot;<br><br>
Oh yes, there are those who view war as a glorious pursuit. They attempt to elevate themselves by calling others cowards, failing to understand the magnitude of their vaingloriousness. I never once knew a soldier in Charley Company, 1st Battalion 52nd Infantry, 198th Light Infantry Brigade, Americal Division who ever had &quot;dreams of glory&quot;. <br><br>
Those who call others &quot;cowards&quot; have very short memories, They fail to remember that there were those of us who acted while all others stood and watched. Many of us never once turned our heads away from injustice. We acted then and we will continue to act today.<br><br>
Students who read this website. Take heed. The ones who will restore this country to righteousness are the ones who reach out their hands to all - regardless of who they are or what they may have done 30 years ago. <br><br>
In the words of a good man who is a frequent poster on this site, &quot;Judge no one&quot;.
